Parabolic galvo scanner and Scan-Tube Lens system

Laser Scanning System: Parabolic Galvo and Scan-Tube Lens Integration

This system employs two cascaded conjugated 4f optical systems. The first one, a parabolic galvo scanner, deflects the incoming collimated beam in two dimensions. The galvo mirrors' rotation axes define the system's pivot points, enabling angular scanning. The second subsystem, the scan-tube lens system, serves to relay the scanned beam and expand its diameter to overfill the objective's back aperture. The scan-tube lens system is designed to conjugate the second galvo scanner's pivot point to the objective's back focal plane. This conjugation ensures telecentric scanning, maintaining a constant angle of incidence at the sample plane throughout the scan.

3D model of the Parabolic Galvo and Scan-Tube Lens telecentric system .
The scanning system schematic. The galvo mirror planes and the objective's back focal plane are optically conjugate. Consequently, the collimated beam's axis always passes through the centers of these surfaces, and the beam is collimated there.
  • point-scanner module (includes the parabolic scanner, point-scanner software and firmware, etc)
  • Scan-Tube lens system

The laser scanner system, employing a parabolic galvo scanner and scan-tube lens system, aims to achieve:

Precise and rapid laser beam deflection.
Minimized optical aberrations (field curvature).
Uniform sample illumination through telecentric scanning.
High-resolution imaging capabilities.

This document outlines the design and operation of a laser scanning system employing a parabolic galvo scanner coupled with a scan-tube lens system. This configuration is optimized for precise beam manipulation and targeted delivery in applications requiring high spatial resolution.

System Architecture:

The system comprises two primary optical components: a parabolic galvo scanner and a scan-tube lens system.

  • Parabolic Galvo Scanner:
    • The parabolic galvo scanner utilizes mirrors mounted on high-precision galvanometers. These galvanometers facilitate rapid and accurate angular deflection of the incident laser beam.
    • The parabolic mirror geometry is strategically implemented to mitigate field curvature and enhance scan linearity across the target plane.
    • This component enables two-dimensional scanning by independent control of the galvanometer axes.
  • Scan-Tube Lens System:
    • The scan-tube lens system is optically coupled to the galvo scanner, serving to relay the angular beam deflection onto the objective lens.
    • A critical function of this lens system is to translate the angular scan motion into a linear displacement at the objective lens's focal plane.
    • The system is designed to achieve telecentric scanning, ensuring a constant beam angle of incidence at the target plane throughout the scanning process. This minimizes off-axis aberrations and maintains uniform image quality.
    • The back aperture of the objective lens is placed at the output of the scan tube lens system.

Operational Principles:

The laser beam is initially directed onto the parabolic galvo scanner. The galvanometers, under precise electronic control, deflect the beam according to the desired scan pattern. The deflected beam then enters the scan-tube lens system, which performs the necessary optical transformations to ensure accurate and consistent beam delivery to the objective lens. The objective lens, in turn, focuses the scanned beam onto the target plane.

Advantages and Applications:

This integrated system offers several key advantages:

  • High Scanning Speed and Precision: Galvanometer-based scanning enables rapid and accurate beam positioning.
  • Minimized Optical Aberrations: The parabolic mirror design and telecentric scan-tube lens system reduce field curvature and off-axis aberrations.
  • Uniform Image Quality: Telecentric scanning ensures consistent beam incidence and focus across the entire scan field.

This design is particularly applicable in:

  • Two-photon microscopy
  • Laser material processing
  • Optical coherence tomography
  • High-resolution laser imaging

Conclusion:

The integration of a parabolic galvo scanner and a scan-tube lens system provides a robust and high-performance solution for laser scanning applications. This configuration offers precise beam manipulation, minimizes optical aberrations, and ensures uniform image quality across the scanned area.
